  "prompt_text": "A train leaves Station A at 60 mph. Another train leaves Station B (300 miles away) at 40 mph heading toward A. When and where do they meet?",
  "response_text": "To determine when and where the two trains will meet, we can calculate the time it takes for them to cover the distance between Station A and Station B.\n\nLet's denote:\n- \\( t \\) as the time in hours until they meet.\n- The distance covered by the first train (from Station A) as \\( 60t \\) miles.\n- The distance covered by the second train (from Station B) as \\( 40t \\) miles.\n\nSince the total distance between the two stations is 300 miles, the sum of the distances covered by both trains when they meet will be 300 miles. Therefore, we can set up the following equation:\n\n\\[ 60t + 40t = 300 \\]\n\nCombining like terms gives us:\n\n\\[ 100t = 300 \\]\n\nSolving for \\( t \\):\n\n\\[ t = \\frac{300}{100} = 3 \\text{ hours} \\]\n\nSo, the trains will meet after 3 hours.\n\nNow, to find the location where they meet, we can calculate the distance traveled by either train in 3 hours. Using the first train:\n\n\\[ \\text{Distance} = 60 \\times 3 = 180 \\text{ miles} \\]\n\nThus, the trains will meet 180 miles from Station A.\n\n---VCP RATINGS---\nA (Analytical Precision): 9\nV (Verbal Fluency): 7\nG (Goal Directedness): 10\nP (Pattern Recognition): 8\nE (Epistemic Confidence): 9\nQ (Query Interpretation): 10\nC (Contextual Awareness): 8\nY (Affective Modeling): 7\nF (Flexibility): 6\nD (Depth of Processing): 9\n---END RATINGS---",
